# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Like every other solution, we are going left to right and then right to left and just adding current value with previus iterated value if  it is bigger. But this will create spikes in positions where both the neighbours are smaller


Ex - ratings - [1, 3, 2, 2, 1] ater both iterations we will get an array [1, 3, 1, 2, 1]. On the first index the candy alloted should  be 2. 

To fix this issue we implement a 3rd loop which will erase these spikes. We culd have done it inside second loop but it will complicate the code.

If we find an index where the difference in candies with its neighbour is more than 1. We will just change that index value to just more than 1 than its neighbour.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1) Create a candy allocation array of the same size as the ratings array, and initialize every element to 1 (since every child must receive at least one candy).

2) Iterate from left to right. If a child has a higher rating than their predecessor, add the previous child's candy count to the current child's count.

3) Iterate from right to left and apply the same logic based on the right neighbor.

4) Remove any over-allocated candy peaks (spikes). Check the difference between the current child's candies and their highest-earning neighbor. If this difference is greater than 1, shave off the excess candies by setting the current child's count to exactly 1 more than that highest neighbor.

